      "content": "I was just using a metaphor to make the concept more relatable, but I understand how it might be confusing. Let's stick to the math.\n\nTo illustrate the interest calculation, let's consider a simple example. Suppose you have a $10,000 student loan with an interest rate of 6% per year, compounded monthly. Your monthly payment is $200.\n\nHere's how the interest calculation works:\n\n1. The lender calculates the daily interest rate: 6%/year / 365 days = 0.0164% per day\n2. The lender multiplies the daily interest rate by the number of days in the month (e.g., 30 days): 0.0164% x 30 = 0.00492% per month\n3. The lender applies this monthly interest rate to the outstanding balance: $10,000 x 0.00492% = $0.49 (this is the interest charged for the month)\n4. You make your monthly payment of $200, which includes the interest ($0.49) and a portion of the principal ($199.51)\n\nNow, let's see how the principal balance changes over time:\n\n* Month 1: Outstanding balance = $10,",
